properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of hazardous winter conditions is expected. Additional snowfall: 15 to 25 cm. Maximum wind gusts: northwesterly 80 km/h. Time span: continuing until Boxing Day night. Locations: Gander and northeastern Newfoundland. Remarks: Snow, heavy at times, will become lighter and more intermittent tonight and Christmas Day. A second round of heavy snow is expected to set in during the morning of Boxing Day. Gusty northeasterly winds will strengthen to strong northwesterlies with gusts to 80 km/h overnight. The strong northwesterlies will then persist through Boxing Day. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:
Description: Rain or drizzle on tap Friday... Periods of rain or freezing drizzle are expected over Southwestern Quebec. Precipitations should begin overnight Thursday night over the Outaouais area and the greater Montréal before reaching Central Quebec during the day Friday. The amount of freezing precipitation expected are not significant but should be enough to make roads and sidewalks icy and slippery. Consider the possibility of getting a head start or delay non-essential travels. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Fog Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visibility in fog is expected or occurring over some areas. Areas of dense fog will slowly dissipate throughout this morning. ### Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Fog advisories are issued when near zero visibilities in fog are expected or occurring. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Additional snowfall: approximately 10 cm through today, Boxing Day, and Boxing Day night. Maximum wind gusts: northwesterly 80 km/h. Time span: continuing until Boxing Day night. Locations: Clarenville and Terra Nova. Remarks: Periods of snow will continue through today, ease to scattered flurries tonight and then reintensify into snow near noon on Boxing Day. Strong northwesterly winds gusting between 70 and 80 km/h will persist through today and Boxing Day and will combine with the fresh snowfall to cause reduced visibilities in blowing snow, especially in exposed areas. ### Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Additional snowfall: 5 to 10 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 70 km/h. Locations: Grand Falls-Windsor to the Baie Verte Peninsula. Time span: continuing until Boxing Day. Remarks: Snow will continue into tonight. Northeasterly winds gusting to 50 km/h will strengthen to strong northwesterlies with gusts to 70 km/h overnight tonight. Snow will become lighter and more intermittent for Christmas Day and Boxing Day, but the strong northwesterly winds will persist, resulting in poor visibility in blowing snow. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very large waves, pounding surf, and elevated sea water levels are expected later this week. Wave heights: 7 to 9 metres, breaking upon approach to shore. Locations: east and northeast coasts of Newfoundland. Time span: Thursday and Friday. Remarks: a prolonged period of strong winds will cause very large waves to build later this week. Storm surge and coastal flooding may occur along shorelines exposed to the north and northeast, especially near the high tides. The highest water levels are expected to occur on Friday morning, but vulnerable areas may become susceptible to flooding as early as the Thursday morning high tide. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Additional snowfall: 10 to 15 cm through today, Boxing Day and Boxing Day night. Maximum wind gusts: generally northwesterly 80 km/h, except locally 100 km/h along the coast. Time span: continuing until Boxing Day night. Locations: St. John's, Avalon Peninsula North, and Bonavista Peninsula. Remarks: Periods of snow will continue through today, ease to scattered flurries tonight and then reintensify into snow on Boxing Day afternoon. Strong northwesterly winds gusting between 80 and 100 km/h will persist through today and Boxing Day and will combine with the fresh snowfall to cause reduced visibilities in blowing snow, especially in exposed areas. ### Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
